goal_checkin_teen_data.response.pre_goal_negative: That is okay. You will learn more about the importance of spending time with your teen and how to do this in this course.
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_improved_positive: Congratulations! 🎉You’ve made progress since you’ve started this course in ParentText. Your effort is working!
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_improved_negative: Congratulations on making some progress. It seems like spending time with your teen may still be a challenge.
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_static_positive: You were already excelling at spending one-on-one-time with your teen before ParentText. It’s great that you’re able to keep up the excellent effort!
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_static_negative: I am sorry to hear that you were unable to spend more time with your teen. 💛
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_worsened_positive: Time with your teen is so important. Though you are still doing great, you have reported that spending time together has become more challenging since you first began this course.
goal_checkin_teen_data.response.post_goal_worsened_negative: I am sorry to hear that you were unable to spend more time with your teen. 💛
goal_checkin_teen_data.follow_up_positive_message: Excellent! Keep up the good work in improving your relationship with your teen
goal_checkin_teen_data.follow_up_negative_message: Trying is what counts! Let's try to get this going GOOD!
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.question: What did you find difficult about spending time with your teen? 🔑
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.pb: I did not have enough time.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.tip:
It can be hard to find time during your day, with work, chores, and everything else. 

✨Think of a time each day that you could spare 5 minutes. You can even make household chores into a game to do together. 
;
Use the time that you and your teens are already sharing, like eating a meal or saying goodnight before bed. 

You can even make household chores into a game to do together. 

Type {PLAY} for a fun activity suggestion
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.pb: My teen did not want to spend one-on-one-time with me.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.tip:
😔 It can hurt when Your Teen does not want to spend one-on-one-time with you. 

💡 Think to yourself: When are they more open to you? In the morning? Right before bedtime?

💙 Try again so that your teen can see that you care and want to spend this time with them.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.pb: All my teen wanted to do was watch T.V. or play with a phone/tablet.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.tip:
📺 Teens often want to spend time watching T.V. or playing with a phone/tablet. 

❓ You could watch or play on the phone/tablet with them. 
;
🌈 Caring about their interests is a great start!

🌷 Once you begin spending time together, you can suggest another activity. 

Type {PLAY} for a fun activity suggestion.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.pb: My teen wanted to do things I felt uncomfortable about.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.tip:
📱 Sometimes your teen will suggest activities that are violent or unsafe. 

🚩 Explain *why* you can't do them, and suggest a different activity. 

Type {PLAY} for a fun activity suggestion. 💡
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.pb: My teen wanted to do activities that I could not do.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.tip:
☀️ If your teen wants to do things that are too difficult for you to do, you could watch them. 

🏁 You could describe what they are doing like a sports announcer.

You can also express enthusiasm by clapping, smiling, or giving them a thumbs-up. 

💛 Praise them while they do it!
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.6.pb: My teen chose a competitive activity. I won, and then they got angry.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.6.tip:
⚽ Competitive games can be hard for teens (and adults!) if they don’t like losing. 

🏆 When they have calmed down, talk with your teen about what winning well and losing well might look like.
;
📝 Suggest other activities that you can do to work together instead of against each other.

Type {PLAY} for a fun activity suggestion. 💡
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.7.pb: All my teens wanted one-on-one time at the same time.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.7.tip:
🔴 It can be difficult to spend one-on-one time with each of your teens when you have more than one. 

🌱 If possible, you can ask an adult or older sibling to look after the other teens while you spend one-on-one time with one teen.

⏰ Think of when it would be easier to spend one-on-one time with each of your teens. Perhaps later in the evening with your teen, after the others have gone to sleep. 
;
💛 You can also spend one-on-one time with all of your teens at once! If you do, make sure all are able to participate in one-on-one time.

Type {PLAY} and choose GROUP for a fun activity suggestion for a group of teens. 💡
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.8.tip: 💛 We are sorry to hear that you have been finding it hard to spend one-on-one-time with your teen.
goal_checkin_teen_data.conclusion: Thank you for providing a progress update. You can find and go through this course any time via the Main Menu by typing {MENU}.

goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.question: What did you find hard about keeping Your Teen safe online and offline?
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.pb: My teen and I did not agree on which areas were unsafe.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.tip:
👂That’s alright. Even adults don’t agree on this sometimes. Listening to Your Teen, even if we disagree, helps us understand their thinking. 

⏰ Find time to talk about safe and unsafe areas again. 

💚 This time, really listen and show you understand their view before sharing your thoughts.
;
📝 Tell Your Teen that you appreciate their opinions and you are proud of them for being honest about how they feel.

😃 Reach a common agreement and establish safe and unsafe areas, as well as what to do in case of emergency.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.pb: My teen marked the house of someone I trust as unsafe. 🚩 I was shocked and did not know what to do!
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.tip:
😔 It is shocking to learn that people who we trust may be a danger to our teens. 

👂 Listen to Your Teen if they want to talk about why it seems unsafe. Ask if it’s the place, a particular person, or both that makes them uncomfortable. 

Stay calm and open during the conversation. Trust what they say - they will not say such things for no reason!
;
🏥 Talk with someone and get support. Type {HELP} if you need more assistance.
 
💙 Remember to take a pause when you are stressed.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.pb: My teen insisted that they could visit a place I think is not safe, like a bar. I don’t know how to convince them that it is not a safe area.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.tip:
🌷 Create a safe space to talk with Your Teen when you are both calm. 

👂 Listen to their thoughts - why do they feel this place is safe?

⭐ Share why you feel it is not safe. 
;
⏰ Come up with a rule together that lets them still have fun, but stay safe. 

🌱 Your teen will listen better when you speak to them calmly.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.pb: As an adult, I feel I am in charge of protecting my teen. When I told my teen which areas are unsafe, they got angry.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.tip:
😣 Protecting Your Teen while also trusting them to make wise choices is not easy!

🔄 Your Teen may know things about your community and technology that you are not aware of. 
;
📝 When you actively involve Your Teen in creating the safety map, they feel heard and valued.

🌱 It is easier to follow a plan that everyone agrees on.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.pb: It was hard to find safety resources because I don’t know my community so well.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.tip:
🔵 Involve your whole family, other caregivers, and friends in your mapping activity. If everyone knows the safe places, they can help keep Your Teen safe!

🚗 Visit some of the services available, such as neighbourhood watch groups or clinics. Ask what they do, how to contact them, and what their emergency procedures are.
;
💡 Ensure that emergency phone numbers are clearly displayed in your house and easily accessible to everyone.

💛 The more we know, the better we can keep our families safe!

If you want more resources about keeping safe, type {HELP} anytime.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.6.pb: I did not have any time to do this activity.
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.6.tip:
⏰ It can be hard to find time.

💡 This week, put just 10 minutes aside to talk with Your Teen about safe and unsafe areas.

❗ This is important to keep your teen safe!
goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.7.tip: That's okay! It's important to try to keep your teen safe offline and online. Remember, you can review this course in the Main menu any time!
goal_checkin_teen_data.conclusion: Thank you for providing your progress update. You can revisit this course any time in the Main Menu by typing {MENU}. 📝

goal_checkin_teen_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.tip:

💚 It means Your Teen knows what is safe and healthy, so they can make good choices to keep themselves safe.

goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.pb: I am shy to talk to my young child about their body and safe touch.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.tip:
💙 It is slightly uncomfortable to talk to our children about male and female body parts. However, it helps to keep our children safe.

💡Start a conversation with Your Child about their body, its functions, and the importance of naming each part. Acting out stories with dolls or teddy bears can be a helpful tool in having these conversations.
;
💚 Talk with confidence about the body, especially private parts. Initially, it may feel awkward, but the more you do it, the more natural and comfortable it will become for both. Your Child will learn how to talk about their body and can communicate with you if anything happens.

🔑 Answer any questions from Your Child honestly. You can do this to keep our children safe!🌷

goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.question: What did you find difficult when supporting your child’s development?
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.pb: I don’t have time to interact with my child.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.1.tip:
🌈 It is okay to feel that way. There are many small ways to spend time with your child!

⏰ You can interact with your child while doing something else. For example, you can ask your child to describe the colours and objects they see around them while you are walking together or travelling on a bus.

😃 Your child will appreciate the attention you are giving, even for a short while.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.pb: My child is not interested in spending time with me.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.2.tip:
😣 You may be hurt because your child does not want to spend time with you.

⏰ Sometimes, your child just needs some time to start to engage with you. It helps to remain calm, patient, and kind while you try to connect with your child.

🌱 As children grow, they may want independence from you. That’s normal! You can support them to find friends based on their interests.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.pb: My child keeps getting hurt from exploring or making new friends.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.3.tip:
🧸 It must be hard to see your child getting injured or feeling sad often. 

🌷Children learn and grow from making mistakes. It is an important part of child development. They will be safe as long as you are aware of their activities and you can prevent anything dangerous.

⭐ Build your child’s confidence about what they do, what is important to them, and how they look so that they are comfortable trying new things.

🎨 Encourage them to safely try out fun activities with other children or adults. Praise them when they do it well!

💚 Let your child know that you trust them to be safe and follow the rules that you have set.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.pb: My child likes competitive activities but gets angry when they lose or need to share the win.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.4.tip:
⚽ Competitive games can be hard for children (and adults!) if they don’t like losing or sharing.

🏆 When they have calmed down, talk with your child about what winning well and losing well might look like.

📝 Suggest other activities that you can do to work together instead of against each other.

Type {PLAY} for a fun activity suggestion. 💡
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.pb: My child expresses negative emotions all the time.
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.5.tip:
💙 It is difficult when your child is expressing negative feelings, but this is common because your child is also learning to manage their emotions.

👂 Listen to your child’s emotions and acknowledge them.

💡 Ask your child what they or you can do to help them feel better, and give your child advice on what you think would work well.

🌱 While it is tempting to solve your child’s problems immediately with what you think is best, it will not help them grow. Give them a chance to come up with their own ideas!
goal_checkin_child_data.troubleshooting.problems.6.tip: 💚 We are sorry to hear that it has been hard for you to understand your child’s development.
